%BOM---------------------
Date:8/7/2011 10:40:11 AM
From:Paul Senior
Madharry, in past I generally had the brokerage reinvest distributions for my
bdc's. The brokerage firm calculates my cost basis this way: for the numerator,
the total cost for shares I bought. The distribution-amount shares I received
from reinvesting are valued at $0. This numerator is divided by the total
shares I hold--- i.e. shares I bought plus the share count from the reinvested
distributions.

For bdc FSC at this broker, I show I have a 12% gain for all shares bought and
distributions reinvested since my purchases. Purchases were begun 8/'09.

However at another brokerage firm wherein the past 12 months I began purchasing
FSC in much larger amounts than previously and not reinvesting the
distributions, it's easy for me to see that the stock drop has created a paper
loss much greater than the couple/three distributions I may have received.
Losses even if I include the dollar gains I show from the first broker.
