%BOM---------------------
Date:8/7/2011 1:27:51 PM
From:Spekulatius
>>Do you know if the non-voting would get the same consideration as the voting
in a merger?<<

Probably not. They would get the same participation in case of a liquidation
but in a merger it all depends on offering something that satisfies the common
and preferred shareholders.

I am not that current in German shareholders rights any more but I believe that
an acquirer cannot easily force you to tender your shares - you can just decide
to keep them. In this case (and if the acquirer owns a large percentage of
shares - 95%+ typically) a Beherrschungsvertrag ( Control contract) is put into
place where the acquirer runs the business and has rights to the cash flows but
the acquired companies still has somewhat of their own legal standing. This
comes also typically with a much larger dividend for the remaining
shareholders.

I believe this is what is currently in place with Audi (NSU.DE) which is
controlled by Volkswagen but the shares still trade in small volume in the
German stock exchange.

FWIW, the last tender off for MAN3.DE shares was at 59.9Euro and MAN.DE at 95
Euro.

http://www.volkswagenag.com/vwag/vwcorp/content/de/investor_relations/blocker.-
in.acq/qual-DownloadFileList.Single.DownloadFile.0026.File/Eintritt_Ziffer_13_1
1_vii_DE.pdf
